The paper deals with the extension of the framework of topological data analysis to non-metric dissimilarity measures, specifically Bregman divergences. This involves the study of Cech, Delaunay, and Vietoris-Rips complexes, which are commonly used in computational geometry and topology. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The paper also involves the analysis of homology groups and persistence diagrams, which are relevant to the sub-categories cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The use of Bregman divergences also connects the paper to the sub-categories cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
